Toxicity, genotoxicity, and carcinogenicity of 2-methylfuran in a 90-day comprehensive toxicity study in gpt delta rats Takashi Umemura a , b , * a Division of Pathology, National Institute of Health Sciences, Kanagawa, Japan b Yamazaki University of Animal Health, Technology, Tokyo, Japan ARTICLE INFO Handling Editor: Dr. Jose Luis Domingo Keywords: 2-Methylfuran Carcinogenesis gpt delta rats GST-P ABSTRACT 2-Methylfuran (2-MF) exists naturally in foods and is used as a flavoring agent. Furan, the core structure of 2-MF, possesses hepatocarcinogenicity in rodents. Accumulation of toxicological information on furan derivatives is needed to elucidate their carcinogenic mode of action. In the current study, we examined the comprehensive toxicological studies of 2-MF using gpt delta rats. 2-MF was intragastrically administered to groups of 10 male and 10 female Sprague-Dawley gpt delta rats at a dose of 0, 1.2, 6, or 30 mg/kg/day for 13 weeks. Effects of 2-MF on the hepatobiliary system including an increase in serum alkaline phosphatase were observed in the 6 and 30 mg/kg groups, and cholangiofibrosis was found in the 30 mg/kg group. The no observed adverse effect level was set at 1.2 mg/kg/day for both sexes and 1.14 mg/kg/day was determined as the benchmark dose low. The acceptable daily intake was calculated to be 11.4 μ g/kg/day. Increases in the number and areas of glutathione S - transferase placental form-positive foci in the 30 mg/kg group were apparent, suggesting the hep -atocarcinogenicity of 2-MF in rats. By contrast, the lack of increase in in vivo mutagenicity in the liver implied that 2-MF hepatocarcinogenesis may not involve genotoxic mechanisms. 1. Introduction Based on the concept of threshold of toxicological concern, decision trees in the safety assessment of flavoring agents were established by the Joint Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)/World Health Organi -zation (WHO) Expert Committee on Food Additives (JECFA), European Food Safety Authority (EFSA), and Food Safety Commission Japan (FSCJ) (JECFA, 2016 ; EFSA, 2019 ; FSCJ, 2016 ). Although there are some different points among the various decision trees, negative results for genotoxicity are commonly required to proceed. Accordingly, the outcomes of genotoxicity tests are critical for current safety assessments of flavoring agents. This is because a threshold does not exist in geno -toxicity, suggesting that there may not be a threshold for carcinogenicity involving genotoxic mechanisms. In fact, although there are some evi -dences showing the existence of practical threshold in genotoxic carci -nogenesis due to in vivo defense system such as metabolism and DNA repair system (Fukushima et al., 2010 ), the current risk evaluation process is based on this concept. By contrast, the no observed adverse effect level (NOAEL) is a health-based guidance value that is occasion -ally used in safety assessments. For the current risk evaluation, bench -mark dose (BMD) approach are considered to be preferable to NOAEL approach (EFSA, 2017 , 2022 ). Thus, general toxicity, genotoxicity, and carcinogenicity data are still required for safety assessments of flavoring agents. The gpt delta transgenic rat model is an in vivo mutation assay model that can detect point mutations by 6-thioguanine (6-TG) selection and deletion mutations by Spi � selection (Nohmi et al., 1996 ; Hayashi et al., 2003 ). In this rat model, quantitative analyses of glutathione S -trans -ferase placental form (GST-P)-positive foci can be performed during conventional repeated toxicity studies. We have proposed a compre -hensive medium-term animal model in which general toxicity, geno -toxicity, and carcinogenicity are simultaneously evaluated using gpt delta rats (Jin et al., 2011 ). In our previous studies, the NOAEL from general toxicity data and genotoxicity and carcinogenicity in potential target organs were assessed for various flavoring agents, including safrole (Jin et al., 2011 ), 1-methylnaphthalene (Jin et al., 2012 ), Abbreviations: 2-MF, 2-methylfuran; NOAEL, no observed adverse effect level; BMD, benchmark dose; BMDL, benchmark dose low. * Corresponding author. Furan-substituted compounds used as flavoring agents were evalu -ated several times by JECFA (JECFA, 2001 , 2006 , 2012 , 2019 ). Some compounds within this group, including 2-methylfuran (2-MF), were not evaluated using the decision tree in safety assessment of flavoring agents because of concerns with respect to genotoxicity and carcinogenicity (JECFA, 2006 ). This decision was based on metabolism information given that the furan ring from such furan-substituted compounds can be oxidized to form an unstable epoxide that may undergo rapid ring opening to yield reactive 2-ene-1,4-dicarbonyl intermediates that can react with DNA (Kedderis et al., 1993 ; Chen et al., 1995 ). Furan is known to induce cholangiocarcinoma or hepatocellular carcinoma in rat 2-year bioassay together with cholangiofibrosis (Von Tungeln et al., 2017 ). Some positive outcomes in in vitro genotoxicity studies for furan may result from this DNA modification. However, exposure to furan has not been shown to affect gene mutations in various mutagenicity tests (NTP, 1993 ; Mortelmans et al., 1986 ) and DNA strand breaks in Comet assays (Kellert et al., 2008 ). In vivo comet assay using carcinogenic target organ demonstrated that furan increased formamidopyrimidine DNA glyco -sylase and endonuclease III-sensitive DNA damage, suggesting possible involvement of secondary DNA damage due to oxidative stress in furan-induced DNA damage (Ding et al., 2012 ). Additionally, transgenic rodent (TGR) gene mutation assays using Big Blue (McDaniel et al., 2012 ) or gpt delta rats (Hibi et al., 2017 ) demonstrated negative results in the target organ. Because furan metabolite-specific DNA adducts have not been detected in the livers of rats given furan at carcinogenic doses (Burka et al., 1991 ; Churchwell et al., 2015 ), it is highly probable that the plausible metabolite does not attach to DNA in vivo possibly because of its short half-life. Recent global gene expression analysis using furan-treated mice suggests that cis -2-butene-1,4-dial (BDA) as a furan metabolite, induced cytotoxicity and oxidative stress followed by inflammation and regenerative cell proliferation, leading to hep -atocarcinogenesis (Jackson et al., 2014 ; 2015 ). In order to support the hypothesis that furan is a non-genotoxic carcinogen, a large amount of negative data on genotoxicity, not only of furan but also of furan de -rivatives, should be accumulated. In particular, because the above-mentioned genotoxic pathways are dependent on the functional side chain attached to the furan ring, data on low-molecular-weight alkyl furans, such as 2-MF, may be informative. Two independent studies have recently reported general toxicologic and in vivo genotoxic studies, including Comet assays, Pig-a gene mu -tation assays, and micronucleus tests after 28-day repeated dosing of 2- MF (Gill et al., 2014 ; Huo et al., 2020 ). The toxicological profiles ob -tained in these studies were similar to those of furan. Furthermore, all in vivo genotoxicity tests were negative, as was observed for furan. How -ever, in addition to the global standard that 90-day toxicity studies are appropriate for safety evaluation of flavoring agents, application of 2-MF to the 90-day comprehensive toxicity model may be essential for data acquisition in TGR gene mutation assays. In the current study, Sprague-Dawley (SD) gpt delta rats were intragastrically administered 2-MF at concentrations of 1.2, 6, and 30 mg/kg for 90 days, and general toxicity studies, gpt assays, Spi � assays, and quantitative analysis of GST-P foci were conducted. 2. Materials and methods 2.1. Test compound ◦ C. 2.2. Experimental animals and housing conditions The protocol for this study was approved by the Animal Care and Utilization Committee of the National Institute of Health Sciences. Specific pathogen-free, 5-week-old male Slc:SD-Tg ( gpt delta) rats car -rying 5 – 10 tandem copies of the transgene lambda EG10 per haploid genome were obtained from Japan SLC (Shizuoka, Japan) and accli -mated for 1 week prior to testing. Animals were housed in a room with a barrier system and maintained under a constant temperature (23 ± 2 ◦ C) and relative humidity (55% ± 5%). The air was changed 12 times/h, and lighting was on a 12-h light/dark cycle. All rats had free access to tap water. 2.3. Animal treatment Groups of 10 male and female SD gpt delta rats were intragastrically administered 2-MF at concentrations of 1.2, 6, and 30 mg/5 mL/kg or vehicle (olive oil) for 90 days. The doses were selected based on pre -liminary studies. Briefly, 2-MF was administered via gavage at doses of 10, 30, 100, and 200 mg/kg to groups of 3 male SD rats in the initial study. All animals administered 200 mg/kg died by day 2, and decreases in body weight were observed at 100 mg/kg. In the subsequent study, 2- MF was administered by gavage at doses of 3, 10, and 30 mg/kg to groups of 5 male and female SD rats for 4 weeks. No deaths or changes in body weight were observed at all doses; however, changes in hemato -logical parameters (platelets) were observed at the all doses in males. In the current study, clinical signs were observed daily, and body weight and food consumption were measured once a week during the dosing period. At the end of the dosing period, all animals were eutha -nized under deep anesthesia and necropsied. At necropsy, blood samples were collected from the abdominal aorta for hematology and serum biochemistry. Hematological analysis was performed using an auto -mated hematology analyzer (K-4500; Sysmex Corp., Hyogo, Japan). Differential leukocyte counts were performed with a MICROX HEG-505 (Sysmex Corp.). Parameters for serum biochemistry were analyzed at SRL, Inc. (Tokyo, Japan) using sera frozen after centrifugation of whole blood. At necropsy, the weights of brain, heart, lungs, liver, kidneys, spleen, thymus, adrenal glands, and testes were measured. Relative organ weights were calculated as the values relative to body weights. In addition to these organs, the arteries, bones/marrow, coagulation glands, esophagus, epididymides, large intestines (cecum, colon, and rectum), lymph nodes, mammary glands, pancreas, peripheral nerve, prostate gland, pituitary gland, thyroid glands, salivary gland, skeletal muscles, skin, small intestines (duodenum, jejunum, and ileum), spinal cord, stomach, urinary bladder, tongue, trachea, vagina, uterus, and ovaries were fixed in 10% neutral-buffered formalin. Testes were fixed in Bouin ’ s solution overnight and then transferred into 10% neutral- buffered formalin. Tissues that required decalcification, such as the nasal cavity, spinal cord with bones, sternum, and femur, were treated with a mixture of 10% formic acid and 10% neutral phosphate-buffered formalin. These tissues were routinely embedded in paraffin, sectioned at 3- μ m thickness for hematoxylin and eosin staining, and examined under light microscopy. Histopathological examinations were carried out for all groups. For the liver, the left lobe was fixed with neutral- buffered formalin for histopathological and immunohistopathological examinations, and the remaining liver portions were stored at � 80 ◦ C for in vivo reporter gene mutation assays. 2.4. Benchmark dose (BMD) calculation BMD and BMDL (lower confidence limit of BMD) values were calculated using the United States Environmental Protection Agency ’ s (US-EPA) Benchmark Dose Software (BMDS) version 3.2. Continuous data were run against five model (Exponential, Hill, Linear, Polynomial and Power), and the best model for each data set was chosen based on BMDS recommendation. The confidence interval (CI) level was 95%. 2.5. In vivo reporter gene mutation assay The protocol for the in vivo reporter gene mutation assay followed Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) guidelines for Transgenic Rodent Somatic and Germ Cell Gene Mutation Assays (OECD, 2011 ). 6-TG and Spi � selections were performed using the methods described by Nohmi et al. (2000) . Briefly, genomic DNA was extracted from the livers of animals in each group using Recover Ease DNA isolation kits (Agilent Technologies, Santa Clara, CA, USA), and lambda EG10 DNA (48 kb) was rescued as phages by in vitro pack -aging using Transpack Packaging Extract (Agilent Technologies). For 6-TG selection, packaged phages were incubated with Escherichia coli YG6020, which expresses Cre recombinase, and converted to plasmids carrying genes encoding gpt and chloramphenicol acetyltransferase. Infected cells were mixed with molten soft agar and poured onto agar plates containing chloramphenicol and 6-TG. In order to determine the total number of rescued plasmids, infected cells were also poured on plates containing chloramphenicol without 6-TG. The plates were then incubated at 37 ◦ C for selection of 6-TG-resistant colonies, and gpt mutant frequencies (MFs) were calculated by dividing the number of gpt mutants after clonal correction by the number of

4f0e4800-b452-400a-b717-f76edc9083ea.text: pack -aging using Transpack Packaging Extract (Agilent Technologies). For 6-TG selection, packaged phages were incubated with Escherichia coli YG6020, which expresses Cre recombinase, and converted to plasmids carrying genes encoding gpt and chloramphenicol acetyltransferase. Infected cells were mixed with molten soft agar and poured onto agar plates containing chloramphenicol and 6-TG. In order to determine the total number of rescued plasmids, infected cells were also poured on plates containing chloramphenicol without 6-TG. The plates were then incubated at 37 ◦ C for selection of 6-TG-resistant colonies, and gpt mutant frequencies (MFs) were calculated by dividing the number of gpt mutants after clonal correction by the number of rescued phages. For Spi � selection, packaged phages were incubated with E. coli XL-1 Blue MRA for survival titration and E. coli XL-1 Blue MRA P2 for mutant se -lection. Infected cells were mixed with molten lambda-trypticase agar plates. The next day, plaques (Spi � candidates) were punched out with sterilized glass pipettes, and the agar plugs were suspended in SM buffer. The Spi � phenotype was confirmed by spotting the suspensions on three types of plates where XL-1 Blue MRA, XL-1 Blue MRA P2, and WL95 P2 strains was spread with soft agar. Spi � mutants, which made clear pla -ques on every plate, were counted. 2.6. Immunohistochemical staining of GST-P foci Immunohistochemical staining was performed using polyclonal an -tibodies against GST-P (1:1000 dilution; Medical and Biological Labo -ratories Co., Ltd., Nagoya, Japan), a marker of preneoplastic lesions in the rat liver, using the avidin-biotin peroxidase complex method. The numbers (/cm 2 ) and areas (mm 2 /cm 2 ) of GST-P-positive foci ( > 0.1 mm 2 ) and the total areas of each liver section were measured using an IPAP image analyzer (Sumika Technos, Osaka, Japan) (Watanabe et al., 1994 ). 2.7. Statistical analysis Variances in the data were evaluated for homogeneity using Bar -tlett ’ s tests. When the data were homogenous, one-way analysis of variance was applied. In heterogeneous cases, the Kruskal-Wallis test was applied. When statistically significant differences were detected, Dunnett ’ s multiple tests were employed for comparisons between the control and treated groups ( p < 0.05). 3. Results 3.1. General condition, body weight, and food consumption There were no deaths and no remarkable changes in clinical signs for any of the treatment groups during the dosing period. For both sexes, body weights were significantly lower for rats in the 30 mg/kg group than those in the control at week 7 or later (Fig. 1). There were no changes in food consumption during the dosing period (Supplemental Fig. 1). 3.2. Hematology and serum biochemistry The results of hematological parameters are shown in Supplemental Table 1. Hemoglobin (Hb), mean corpuscular volume (MCV), and mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH) were significantly lower in the 30 mg/ kg group than in the control for both sexes, whereas the MCH concen -tration was significantly lower in the 30 mg/kg group than in the control for males only. The results of serum biochemical parameters are shown in Table 1. In males, significant increases in alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and inorganic phosphate (IP) were observed at 6 mg/kg and 30 mg/kg; a significant decrease in alanine aminotransferase (ALT) was observed at 6 mg/kg and 30 mg/kg; increases in γ -GTP, total cholesterol, albumin, sodium were observed at 30 mg/kg; and a decrease in glucose were observed at 30 mg/kg. In females, significant decreases in triglycerides (TG) were observed at 1.2 mg/kg and higher; significant decreases in ALT were observed at 6 mg/kg and 30 mg/kg; increases in γ -GTP, Fig. 1. Organ weights and histopathological examination Final body weights and absolute and relative organ weights are shown in Supplemental Table 2. For both sexes, the final body weights were significantly decreased in the 30 mg/kg group. In males, significant increases in absolute and relative liver weights, relative kidney weights, and relative testis weights were observed in the 30 mg/kg group. In females, significant increases in relative liver weights were observed at 6 mg/kg and 30 mg/kg and increases in absolute liver weights and relative kidney weights were observed at 30 mg/kg. There were some changes in absolute thymus and heart weights and in relative brain weights at 30 mg/kg for both sexes; however, these changes may have been related to the observed decreases in final body weights. The results of histopathological examinations are shown in Table 2. Histopathological changes caused by 2-MF were observed in the liver. Benchmark dose (BMD) calculation For BMD calculation, ALP was selected as an endpoint. BMD and BMDL is 3.97 mg/kg/day and 1.14 mg/kg/day, respectively for males, and 30.17 mg/kg/day and 21.98 mg/kg/day, respectively for females. 3.5. In vivo mutation assays in the liver Data for gpt and Spi � MFs in the livers of male and female gpt delta rats treated with 2-MF for 13 weeks are shown in Fig. 3. There were no changes in gpt or Spi � MFs in the livers of rats treated with 2-MF at all doses. 3.6. Effects of 2-MF treatment on GST-P-positive foci Quantitative analysis of GST-P-positive foci in the livers of SD gpt delta rats treated with 2-MF is summarized in Fig. 4. 2-MF treatment significantly increased the number and area of GST-P-positive foci at 30 mg/kg in both males and females. 4. Discussion The duration of exposure and the highest dose used in the current study were 90 days and 30 mg/kg body weight, respectively; this exposure time is longer and the dose is higher than in two previous studies (Gill et al., 2014 ; Huo et al., 2020 ). Therefore, we observed significant changes in toxicologic parameters that were both similar to and different from those reported in previous data. Unlike in previous studies, the current study clearly demonstrated significant decreases in the body weights of both sexes at the highest dose in spite of no changes in food consumption. Because various toxicologic parameters are altered at this dose (30 mg/kg BW), the highest dose used in the current study may be a toxic dose. As was observed in a previous 28-day study using SD rats, Hb, MCV, and MCH levels were significantly decreased; these findings were not observed in another 28-day study using F344 rats. The differences may be related to differences in the strains used in these studies. Notably, the specific changes observed in the current study included significant dose-dependent increases in serum ALP levels and γ -GTP levels to increase in males. In females, these two parameters also tended to increase. It is probable that these alterations reflected the effects of 2-MF on

Because various toxicologic parameters are altered at this dose (30 mg/kg BW), the highest dose used in the current study may be a toxic dose. As was observed in a previous 28-day study using SD rats, Hb, MCV, and MCH levels were significantly decreased; these findings were not observed in another 28-day study using F344 rats. The differences may be related to differences in the strains used in these studies. Notably, the specific changes observed in the current study included significant dose-dependent increases in serum ALP levels and γ -GTP levels to increase in males. In females, these two parameters also tended to increase. It is probable that these alterations reflected the effects of 2-MF on intrahepatic bile ducts. In addition to bile duct and oval cell proliferation, the longer exposure to 2-MF used in the current study clarified that 2-MF can induce cholangiofibrosis with higher in -cidences in rats of both sexes. The overall toxicologic alterations were almost identical to those observed in furan-treated rats (Hibi et al., 2017 ). Among these changes observed in the current study, ALP was selected as an endpoint in BMD approach because ALP was specifically changed in this 90-day study but not in the previous 28-day study, and is considered to reflect the characteristic effect of 2-MF on the hep -atobiliary system. Based on fluctuations in general toxicologic parame -ters, the NOAEL obtained in the current study was the lowest dose, 1.2 mg/kg. Calculated BMD and BMDL based on ALP in males were 3.97 mg/kg and 1.14 mg/kg, respectively, demonstrating that the health-based guidance value from BMD approach was almost equal to that from the conventional NOAEL approach in this study. TGR gene mutation assays were conducted using gpt delta rats. Ac -cording to OECD guidelines, the duration of the exposure was 28 days, and the assay was performed 2 days after the last exposure (OECD, 2011 ). In our previous studies, we reported that potassium bromate showed negative results after a 5-week exposure, but that the outcome was positive after a 13-week exposure in TGR gene mutation assays (Umemura et al., 2006 ). Moreover, dicyclanil increased gpt MFs in fe -male mice, but not in male mice (Umemura et al., 2007 ). Therefore, we concluded that 90 days was an appropriate duration for detecting the intrinsic genotoxic potential of chemicals and that both sexes of rodents should be used in TGR gene mutation assays. Notably, in our study, a 90-day exposure to 2-MF failed to elevate gpt or Spi � MFs, implying that 2-MF exposure for an adequate duration did not cause point or deletion mutations in liver DNA. These findings were consistent with the Fig. 2. Histopathological findings in the liver of SD gpt delta rats treated with 2-MF for 13 weeks. outcomes in furan-treated rats (Hibi et al., 2017 ). The consistency of the current toxicologic and genotoxic results between furan and 2-MF in -dicates that these phenomena may result from the common metabolite of furan and 2-MF, 2-ene-1,4-dicarbonyl intermediate. Actually, furan is metabolized by CYP 2E1 in the liver to form an electron-affinitive molecule, cis -2-butene-1,4-dial (BDA) (Chen et al., 1995 ). BDA forma -tion may be the trigger of cytotoxicity and oxidative stress, which leads to inflammation and regenerative proliferation in the liver (Jackson et al., 2014 ; 2015 ). Also, 2-MF is converted to 4-oxopent-2-enal (Peterson, 2013 ). These 2-ene 1,4-dicarbonyl intermediates may be responsible for characteristic profiles in toxicity and genotoxicity of furan and 2-MF. Thus, the negative results obtained in TGR gene mu -tation assays in this study reproduced the negative outcomes of previ -ously reported TGR gene mutation assays for furan using two different reporter gene transgenic rat models (McDaniel et al., 2012 ; Hibi et al., 2017 ). Therefore, the accumulated negative data on the in vivo geno -toxicity of furan may support the hypothesis that the plausible metab -olite is not capable of causing gene mutations in spite of the formation of BDA from furan or 4-oxopent-2-enal from 2-MF possibly due to their very short half-lives. Immunohistochemical staining of GST-P positive foci (A), and number and area of GST-P positive foci (B) in the liver of SD gpt delta dats treated with 2-MF for 13 weeks. Data represent the mean ± SD. Asterisks indicate significant difference from the controls (**: p < 0.01). Quantitative analyses of GST-P-positive foci demonstrated that treatment with 2-MF for 90 days increased the number and the area of GST-P-positive foci compared with those in the control. These phe -nomena were also observed in furan-treated rats. Based on our current toxicological data showing the potent induction of cholangiofaibrosis, a potential preneoplastic lesion of intrahepatic biliary tumors, 2-MF may exert carcinogenic effects on the intrahepatic bile duct as well as he -patocytes. However, because the comprehensive medium-term animal model used in the current study could simultaneously demonstrate the genotoxicity and carcinogenicity of a test compound in the same organ, the mechanisms underlying the induction of GST-P-positive foci by 2-MF exposure do not involve genotoxic events. As was the case for furan, it is likely that 2-MF exerts direct mitogenic actions on the liver (Hibi et al., 2017 ). 2-MF is not only a flavoring agent but also a food contaminant, similar to furan (Stadler and Theurillat, 2017 ). Safety assessments of these compounds have contributed to ensuring food safety. Based on the BMDL (1.14 mg/kg/day) in this study, 11.4 μ g/kg/day was calculated as ADI of 2-MF using 100 as a safety factor. Dietary intake of 2-MF is re -ported to be 0.105 μ g/kg/day (Gonz ́ alez et al., 2022 ), indicating that there is a sufficient safety margin. In this study, we showed that 2-MF was carcinogenic in the liver through a mechanism other than geno -toxicity, and this enabled us to establish the acceptable daily intake because 2-MF was identified as a nongenotoxic hepatocarcinogen, similar to furan.
